 appropriate care and implementing preventive strategies.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the risk for Indigenous Australian women compared to non-Indigenous women in relation to diabetes in pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["10 times higher risk of developing type 2 diabetes after gestational diabetes","2 times higher risk of developing type 2 diabetes after gestational diabetes","5 times higher rate of gestational diabetes","3 times lower risk of developing type 2 diabetes after gestational diabetes","Same risk of developing type 2 diabetes after gestational diabetes"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIndigenous Australian women who experience gestational diabetes have a \u003Cstrong\u003E10 times higher risk of developing type 2 diabetes\u003C/strong\u003E later in life compared to non-Indigenous women. This significantly increased risk highlights the importance of post-pregnancy follow-up and preventive care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis increased risk emphasises the need for culturally appropriate diabetes prevention programs and long-term follow-up care for Indigenous women after pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Indigenous Australian women who experience gestational diabetes have a 10 time higher risk of developing type 2 diabetes later in life compared to non-Indigenous women","Gestational diabetes affects Indigenous Australian women at 2-3 times the rate of non-Indigenous women"],"references":["Ahmed MA, Bailey HD, Pereira G, White SW, Wong K, Shepherd CCJ. Trends and burden of diabetes in pregnancy among Aboriginal and non-Aboriginal mothers in Western Australia, 1998-2015. BMC Public Health. 2022 Feb 9;22(1):263. doi: 10.1186/s12889-022-12663-6. PMID: 35139837; PMCID: PMC8827280.","Australian Government. Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander mothers and babies. AIHW.gov. Available from: https://www.aihw.gov.